Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering with Large Language Models

Stakeholder Interview with the goal of generating a specification for the assistant tool that assists Requirement Engineers during Documentation Process

Q1 — Sharpen what "productivity" actually means to him

"If this system worked perfectly after three months — what specifically would be different about your working day compared to today?"

Why this matters: Right now G0 says "Maximise BA productivity" — but that's still vague. His answer will tell you whether productivity means speed (do things faster), completeness (miss nothing), confidence (trust your own work), or autonomy (need less help from others). Each of those gives G0 a different measurable shape and affects how you prioritise G1, G2, G3.

Answer to 1st question: the productivity in his perspective means that, whenever he does an interview and is finished with it, he only wants all the required elements to be ticked off and that the result is reliable, that he could close his teams app and then feels relaxed knowing that the interview went perfectly and the required informations are gathered and documented properly.. So basically it’s all of the aspects, from speed, reliability, completeness, confidence and autonomy. 


Q2 — Clarify the "brain replacing DevOps" vision

"When you say you want a brain that replaces DevOps — do you mean replacing the tool itself, or replacing the manual effort of using it?"

Why this matters: This is the difference between two very different systems. If he means replace the tool → the system needs its own data store and becomes a DevOps alternative. If he means replace the overhead → the system is an intelligent layer on top of DevOps, which is what we've been building. Getting this wrong would invalidate the entire scope definition.

Answer to 2nd question: the tools is the additional intelligent layer on top of the current devops tools and the whole data and rules. The stakeholder and companies are based in Germany, the government is virtually protecting companies from bankruptcy but at the cost of adherence. The tools, database and the whole legal staff are already fixed and cannot be altered. 

Q3 - Should we use the tool or we feed the system?
Answer: the system should make perfect sense by default, like already pre educated by default. The system should also create a senseful assumption of the world and reflect on the condition of the world, not only reading or memorizing the request or requirement blindly. But it should be careful when it comes to creating assumptions about the world. 

